#Covariance between the attributes

cov(cars_data$Price,cars_data$Age)
## [1] -59136.11

#The covariance represents Price and Age are not moving together (due to negative covariance)

#Correlation between the attributes

cor_data = cor(cars_data)

cor_data
##            Price        Age
## Price  1.0000000 -0.8765905
## Age   -0.8765905  1.0000000

#Price and Age are strong negatively correlated(-0.876)

#Corrplot - Graphical representaton of correlation

library(corrplot)
## corrplot 0.84 loaded
corrplot(cor_data, method = "number") #displays correlation coefficient in numbers

#Model Building

#Train -Test Split(70:30) - Split the data into Train and Test sets

set.seed(123)
rows = seq(1,nrow(cars_data),1)
trainRows = sample(rows,(70*nrow(cars_data))/100)

cars_train = cars_data[trainRows,]
cars_test = cars_data[-trainRows,]

nrow(cars_train)
## [1] 1005
nrow(cars_test)
## [1] 431

#Building the linear regression model

LinReg = lm(Price ~ Age, data = cars_train)

#Model Summary

summary(LinReg)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Price ~ Age, data = cars_train)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -7970.9  -941.0    -9.3   860.5 11751.8 
## 
## Coefficients:
##              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 25985.348    266.910   97.36   <2e-16 ***
## Age          -170.057      2.905  -58.53   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 1689 on 1003 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.7735, Adjusted R-squared:  0.7733 
## F-statistic:  3426 on 1 and 1003 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

###Interpretation-

#77% of varition in price of the car is explained by age of the car(R^2 or Adj R^2) #Both Age and intercept are significant (Individual t-test p values) #Model is also significant(F-statistic p value) #1 year increase in age leads to reduction in price by 170 dollars

#Plot the datapoints and line of best fit

plot(cars_train$Age, cars_train$Price,
     xlab = "Age of the car",
     ylab = "Price in ($)",
     main = "Car price Vs. Age: Best fit line", col = "blue")

abline(LinReg,col = "Red", lwd =  1)  #The function adds straigt line to a plot

#To extract the coeffcients

LinReg$coefficients
## (Intercept)         Age 
##   25985.348    -170.057

#To extract residuals

head(LinReg$residuals)
##         415         463         179         526         195         938 
##  -970.61994 -1630.79083  3107.04461 -1110.44905    18.92436   310.46234

#To extract fitted values

head(LinReg$fitted.values)
##       415       463       179       526       195       938 
## 11870.620 12380.791 18842.955 11360.449 13231.076  8639.538

#Validating Linear regression assumptions

par(mfrow = c(2,2))                         #Par helps us to set the graphical parameters
plot(LinReg, lwd=1, col = 'light green')    #Check for validity of linear regression assumptions

#From the residual plots we can say the data is homoscedastic #The error terms are normally distributed(Q-Q Plot) #There are some influential points as per cooks distance(Residual vs Leverage)

#Plot residuals vs fitted values #Helps us to visualize how the residuals are distributed in relation to the fitted values

plot(LinReg$fitted.values, LinReg$residuals, main = "Residual vs fitted values", 
     col = "brown", lwd = 1,
     xlab = "Predicted values/Fitted values",
     ylab = "Resiuals")

abline(h = 0,col = 'blue',lwd = 2)
grid(10,10,lwd=1)

#Predict on Test Data

test_prediction = predict(LinReg,cars_test)    #Fitted values
test_actual = cars_data$Price                  #Actual values

###Performance metrics #MAE - Mean Absolute Error

mae <- function(actual, predicted){
  error = actual-predicted
  mean(abs(error))
}

mae(test_actual,test_prediction)
## Warning in actual - predicted: longer object length is not a multiple of
## shorter object length
## [1] 3404.189

#MSE - Mean Squared Error

mse <- function(actual, predicted){
  error = actual - predicted
  mean(error^2)
}

mse(test_actual,test_prediction)
## Warning in actual - predicted: longer object length is not a multiple of
## shorter object length
## [1] 18952908

#RMSE - Root Mean Squared Error

rmse <- function(actual, predicted){
  error = actual - predicted
  sqrt(mean(error^2))
}

rmse(test_actual,test_prediction)
## Warning in actual - predicted: longer object length is not a multiple of
## shorter object length
## [1] 4353.494
